  "notes": "Silver Surfer communicates world-state primarily through enemy density escalation, perspective shifts, and boss encounters. Danger is manifested through visual projectile saturation and enemy variety. Faction identity relies on comic-canon villain recognition rather than color-coding or sigils. The password system and level select create a non-linear narrative progression unique to NES action games. Difficulty itself becomes a world-state signal: the game's 'Nintendo hard' reputation means player struggle directly reflects intended cosmic-scale threat elevation. Power-ups visually transform Surfer's capabilities (silver spheres as options, fire pellets as firepower indicator), creating direct visual feedback between safety and capability. The ambiguous final boss identity (Mister Sinister reference via health bar) and hidden Cosmic Device narrative add macro-level storytelling without explicit visual faction markers.",
